# Space Complexity — Complete DSA Revision Notes

---

# 1. What is Space Complexity?

**Space Complexity** is the total amount of memory required by an algorithm to execute completely.

It measures how memory usage grows as the input size (**n**) increases.

### Definition

> Space Complexity = Input Space + Auxiliary Space

Where:

- **Input Space** → Memory required to store input data.
- **Auxiliary Space** → Extra memory used by the algorithm.

---

# Why is Space Complexity Important?

In real-world applications:

- Mobile devices have limited memory.
- Embedded systems have strict memory constraints.
- Large datasets may not fit into memory.
- Efficient algorithms save resources.

In interviews:

- Companies test whether you can optimize memory usage.
- Some problems prioritize low memory over execution speed.

---

# 2. Components of Space Complexity

## Input Space

Memory required to store the input itself.

Example:

```java
int[] arr = new int[n];
```

Input Space = O(n)

---

## Auxiliary Space

Extra memory used apart from input.

Example:

```java
int sum = 0;
```

Auxiliary Space = O(1)

---

## Total Space Complexity

Formula:

Space Complexity = Input Space + Auxiliary Space

Example:

```java
int[] arr = new int[n];
int sum = 0;
```

Input Space = O(n)

Auxiliary Space = O(1)

Total Space = O(n)

---

# 3. Common Space Complexities

---

# O(1) — Constant Space

## Definition

Memory usage remains constant regardless of input size.

## Example

```java
int sum = 0;

for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    sum += i;
}
```

## Explanation

Only one variable is used.

Memory does not grow with n.

## Space Complexity

O(1)

---

# O(log n) — Logarithmic Space

## Definition

Memory grows logarithmically.

Usually occurs in recursive divide-and-conquer algorithms.

## Example

Binary Search (Recursive)

```java
int binarySearch(int[] arr, int low, int high, int target) {
    if(low > high) return -1;

    int mid = low + (high - low)/2;

    if(arr[mid] == target)
        return mid;

    if(arr[mid] > target)
        return binarySearch(arr, low, mid - 1, target);

    return binarySearch(arr, mid + 1, high, target);
}
```

## Explanation

Each recursive call halves the search space.

Recursion depth:

log₂(n)

## Space Complexity

O(log n)

---

# O(n) — Linear Space

## Definition

Memory grows proportionally with input size.

## Example

```java
int[] temp = new int[n];
```

## Explanation

Array size increases with n.

## Space Complexity

O(n)

---

# O(n log n)

## Definition

Memory grows proportional to n log n.

Less common but appears in some advanced algorithms.

## Example

Recursive tree structures storing log n levels with n data.

## Space Complexity

O(n log n)

---

# O(n²) — Quadratic Space

## Definition

Memory grows as square of input size.

## Example

```java
int[][] matrix = new int[n][n];
```

## Explanation

Matrix contains:

n × n elements

## Space Complexity

O(n²)

---

# O(2ⁿ) — Exponential Space

## Definition

Memory doubles with every increase in input size.

## Example

Generating all subsets and storing them.

```java
List<List<Integer>> subsets;
```

Total subsets:

2ⁿ

## Space Complexity

O(2ⁿ)

---

# O(n!) — Factorial Space

## Definition

Occurs when storing all permutations.

## Example

```java
List<List<Integer>> permutations;
```

Total permutations:

n!

## Space Complexity

O(n!)

